KW  - Hybrid strategy
AB  - Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF), a disease with poor survival, is closely associated with the hyperactivation of Rho-associated protein kinase 2 (ROCK2), making ROCK2 inhibitors a promising therapeutic option. However, classical docking-centric virtual screening for ROCK2 inhibitor discovery faces challenges such as high false positives and limited chemical diversity. To address these limitations, we integrated generative artificial intelligence (AI) and cheminformatics techniques into our virtual screening workflow using AutoMolDesigner, a tool we recently developed. As a result, we successfully identified a structurally unique hit, 8413, which exhibited potent ROCK2 inhibition (half maximal inhibitory concentration (IC50) = 0.12 µmol/L), low cytotoxicity, significant anti-fibrotic activity, effective inhibition of the ROCK signaling pathway in the human pulmonary fibroblasts (HPF) cells and excellent ROCK2 kinase selectivity. Moreover, 8413 markedly attenuated pulmonary fibrosis in bleomycin (BLM)-induced IPF mice. This study not only identified a highly promising lead compound that inhibits ROCK2 for IPF treatment, but also introduced an innovative application paradigm that effectively highlighted the transformative potential of combining generative AI with classical virtual screening in drug discovery.
