KW  - Perceived autonomy
KW  - AI dependency
KW  - CASA
KW  - Human-AI interaction
AB  - As generative artificial intelligence (GAI) becomes increasingly adaptive and human-like, questions are emerging about users’ growing psychological dependence on these systems. Guided by the Computers Are Social Actors (CASA) perspective, this study investigates the relationship between perceived anthropomorphism and generative AI dependency, with particular attention to the roles of perceived empathy and perceived autonomy. Survey data from 1034 GAI users in China were analyzed using partial least squares structural equation modeling. The results indicate that perceived anthropomorphism is positively associated with dependency on generative AI. In addition, the findings suggest that this relationship is linked to interconnected psychological pathways: users who perceive GAI as more human-like are also more likely to view it as empathetic and autonomous, and these perceptions are associated with stronger reliance. The results further reveal a significant sequential mediation pattern, indicating that anthropomorphism, empathy, and autonomy together help explain how social perceptions of GAI are associated with sustained dependency. These findings extend CASA to the context of generative, agentic AI by showing that human-like perception may be related to enduring reliance rather than only short-term social response. The study contributes to research on human–AI interaction and offers guidance for designing GAI systems that support users while preserving human agency.
